            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Rizwan Moretti is a man defined by the steady, rhythmic pulse of logistics. Born in Daly City to a Pakistani immigrant father who worked as a longshoreman and a second-generation Italian-American mother, his childhood was a blend of fragrant curries and hearty pasta, of pragmatic grit and warm, boisterous family gatherings. He grew up watching the massive container ships glide into the Port of Oakland, understanding from a young age that the world ran on things being moved from one place to another.\n\nWhile his peers in the late 80s and early 90s were drawn to the nascent glamour of tech, Rizwan chose a more grounded path. He earned an Associate's degree in Logistics from a community college, a practical choice that led directly to a dispatcher job at a trucking firm. Over three decades, he methodically worked his way up the ladder\u2014dispatcher, coordinator, supervisor, and finally, Fleet Operations Manager. The dot-com bust of the early 2000s, which saw many of his friends lose their \"unbeatable\" tech jobs, only solidified his belief in the tangible world of transportation. People, he reasoned, would always need food on their shelves and packages on their doorsteps.\n\nHis intense dedication to his career, however, contributed to the amicable end of his marriage a decade ago. Now, his most cherished relationship is with his 24-year-old daughter, a graphic designer who lives in Oakland. He lives alone in a modest, well-kept bungalow in the Outer Sunset he was fortunate enough to buy in the late 90s. His 5.5-mile commute against traffic to the industrial yards south of the city is a cherished slice of solitude, a time to listen to classic rock and mentally prep for a day of solving puzzles involving diesel, deadlines, and human error.\n\nRizwan\u2019s life is one of routine and quiet satisfaction. Evenings are for tending to his small garden of succulents and tomatoes or walking along Ocean Beach, watching the fog roll in. His dream isn't a lavish retirement but a simple one: to buy a reliable RV and drive across the country, finally managing a fleet of one. He wants to see the supply chain he\u2019s managed his whole life from the other side of the windshield, with no schedule but his own."
