        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe was seven, maybe eight years old, hoisted onto his father\u2019s shoulders at the Port of Oakland. The air was a sharp mix of salt and diesel. Below, the world was a grid of giant metal boxes being moved by colossal cranes. His father pointed, voice rumbling, \u201cSee, Riz? Everything here is going somewhere important.\u201d It wasn\u2019t chaos to him; it was a powerful, tangible rhythm. That day, the incomprehensible scale of logistics became a comforting, logical puzzle in his mind, a path he didn't know he was already on.\n\n2.\nHe remembers having coffee with a laid-off dot-com friend in late 2001. His friend, gesturing wildly, spoke of vaporized stock options and defunct business models. Rizwan listened, feeling not smugness, but a profound, quiet certainty. His world was made of steel, asphalt, and goods people needed. While his friend\u2019s abstract world had collapsed, Rizwan\u2019s was more real than ever. That conversation cemented his belief in the tangible, forever insulating him from the seduction of the next big, ephemeral thing.\n\n3.\nHis daughter, Yasmin, was six, sitting on the living room floor with a toy truck he\u2019d brought her. As she pushed it across the carpet, he explained, \u201cThat truck is bringing spaghetti for our dinner, and new paint for Mrs. Henderson\u2019s house.\u201d Her eyes widened, connecting the toy to their life. In that moment, his job wasn\u2019t just a series of phone calls and schedules anymore; it became a tangible act of providing, a story he could share with the person who mattered most.\n\n4.\nThe first week alone in his Outer Sunset house after the divorce was the quietest of his life. One evening he walked to Ocean Beach, expecting a wave of loneliness. Instead, as the fog rolled in, erasing the horizon, he felt a strange calm. He wasn't lonely; he was just by himself. The cool, damp air felt like a clean slate. That walk wasn't an act of mourning a loss, but the beginning of discovering a peaceful, welcome solitude he never knew he needed.\n\n5.\nIt was a brutal Tuesday, maybe five years ago. A driver quit mid-shift, and a key shipment was late. Driving home, exhausted, a sun-bleached RV chugged past him. The driver, a grey-haired man, had his elbow out the window, looking utterly free. The sight struck Rizwan with the force of a revelation. His vague wish for retirement suddenly had a shape: a steering wheel, an open road, and a manifest with a single destination\u2014anywhere. That vision became his finish line."
